06619nam a22008055i 9780857457059DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574570597 a10.1515/97808574570592doi  a(DE-B1597)636542  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0140002bisacsh00aGerman Scholars and Ethnic Cleansing, 1919-1945 /ced. by Michael Fahlbusch, Ingo Haar. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (322 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tPREFACE -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tChapter 1 GERMAN OSTFORSCHUNG AND ANTI-SEMITISM -- tChapter 2 THE ROLE AND IMPACT OF GERMAN ETHNOPOLITICAL EXPERTS IN THE SS REICH SECURITY MAIN OFFICE -- tChapter 3 THE NAZI ETHNOGRAPHIC RESEARCH OF GEORG LEIBBRANDT AND KARL STUMPP IN UKRAINE, AND ITS NORTH AMERICAN LEGACY -- tChapter 4 VOLK, BEVÖLKERUNG, RASSE, AND RAUM Erich Keyser’s Ambiguous Concept of a German History of Population, ca. 1918–1955 -- tChapter 5 ETHNIC POLITICS AND SCHOLARLY LEGITIMATION The German Institut für Heimatforschung in Slovakia, 1941–1944 -- tChapter 6 THE SWORD OF SCIENCE German Scholars and National Socialist Annexation Policy in Slovenia and Northern Italy -- tChapter 7 ROMANIAN-GERMAN COLLABORATION IN ETHNOPOLITICS The Case of Sabin Manuila -- tChapter 8 PALATINES ALL OVER THE WORLD Fritz Braun, a German Emigration Researcher in National Socialist Population Policy -- tChapter 9 GERMAN WESTFORSCHUNG, 1918 TO THE PRESENT The Case of Franz Petri, 1903–1993 -- tChapter 10 OTTO SCHEEL National Liberal, Nordic Prophet -- tChapter 11 THE “THIRD FRONT” German Cultural Policy in Occupied Europe, 1940–1945 -- tChapter 12 “RICHTUNG HALTEN” Hans Rothfels and Neoconservative Historiography on Both Sides of the Atlantic -- tChapter 13 POLISH MYS´L ZACHODNIA AND GERMAN OSTFORSCHUNG An Attempt at a Comparison -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tSUBJECT INDEX -- tNAMES INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecently, there has been a major shift in the focus of historical research on World War II towards the study of the involvements of scholars and academic institutions in the crimes of the Third Reich. The roots of this involvement go back to the 1920s. At that time right-wing scholars participated in the movement to revise the Versailles Treaty and to create a new German national identity. The contribution of geopolitics to this development is notorious. But there were also the disciplines of history, geography, ethnography, art history, archeology, sociology, and demography that devised a new nationalist ideology and propaganda. Its scholars established an extensive network of personal and institutional contacts. This volume deals with these scholars and their agendas. They provided the Nazi regime with ideas of territorial expansion, colonial exploitation and racist exclusion culminating in the Holocaust. Apart from developing ideas and concepts, scholars also actively worked in the SS and Wehrmacht when Hitler began to implement its criminal policies in World War II. This collection of original essays, written by the foremost European scholars in this field, describes key figures and key programs supporting the expansion and exploitation of the Third Reich. In particular, they analyze the historical, geographic, ethnographical and ethno-political ideas behind the ethnic cleansing and looting of cultural treasures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGenocidezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical culturezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aAchim, Viorel, econtributo